## Beginner Networking Glossary

Here are a few networking terms from today explained in plain language.

You do not need to memorize these.

The goal is to recognize them when you see them again.

---

## Router

A router is the device that manages traffic inside your home network.

It helps your phone, laptop, TV, and other devices connect to the internet.

Think of it like the traffic manager for your home.

---

## Modem

A modem is the device that connects your home to your internet provider.

Some homes have a separate modem and router.

Other homes have one box that does both jobs.

---

## Wi-Fi

Wi-Fi is the wireless signal inside your home.

It lets devices connect to your router without using a cable.

Wi-Fi is not the same thing as the internet.

Wi-Fi connects you to the router.

The router connects you to the internet.

---

## Internet Service Provider

Your Internet Service Provider, or ISP, is the company that brings internet service into your home.

Examples include companies like cable, fiber, or phone providers.

---

## IP Address

An IP address is like a network address for a device.

It helps information know where to go.

Your phone, laptop, smart TV, and router all use IP addresses to communicate.

---

## Private IP Address

A private IP address is used inside your home network.

These often look like:

```text
192.168.1.10
192.168.0.25
10.0.0.8
```

These addresses are usually assigned by your router.

---

## Public IP Address

A public IP address is the address your home uses on the internet.

Think of it like the outside address for your home network.

Websites usually see your public IP address, not the private address of each device inside your house.

---

## Default Gateway

The default gateway is usually your router.

It is the path your device uses to reach the internet.

When your computer does not know where to send traffic, it sends it to the default gateway.

---

## DNS

DNS stands for Domain Name System.

DNS helps turn website names into addresses computers can understand.

When you type:

```text
example.com
```

DNS helps your device find where that website lives.

---

## MAC Address

A MAC address is a unique hardware identifier for a network device.

It helps identify the physical network hardware inside a device.

You do not need to memorize MAC addresses.

Just know they are another way devices can be identified on a network.

---

## Firmware

Firmware is the built-in software that runs inside devices like routers.

Router firmware updates can fix bugs and security issues.

---

## Guest Network

A guest network is a separate Wi-Fi network for visitors or temporary devices.

It helps keep guests away from your main home network.

---

## WPA2 / WPA3

WPA2 and WPA3 are Wi-Fi security protections.

They help protect your wireless network from unauthorized access.

WPA3 is newer.

WPA2 is still common.

WEP is outdated and should not be used.

---

## Final Thought On Vocabulary

Technical vocabulary becomes less intimidating when you see it in context.

You do not need to know every term perfectly today.

You just need to keep showing up and learning the language one piece at a time.

